y Book Club Associates, 1981).\n\n== External links ==\n* [[Johann Georg Theodor Gr\u00e4sse|Dr. J. G. Th. Gr\u00e4sse]], ''[[Orbis Latinus|Orbis Latinus: Lexikon lateinischer geographischer Namen des Mittelalters und der Neuzeit]]'', [http://www.bayerische-landesbibliothek-online.de/orbis-latinus online at the Bavarian State Library]\n*Gr\u00e4sse, ''Orbis Latinus'', [http://www.columbia.edu/acis/ets/Graesse/contents.html online at Columbia University]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061006222944/http://www.ipa.net/~magreyn/#Record Interpreter List of Roman Place names in Great Britain and Ireland]\n\n{{Major towns of Roman Britain}}\n\n[[Category:Alternative names of European places|Roman Britain]]\n[[Category:British toponymy|Roman place names]]\n[[Category:Lists of Latin place names|Britain]]\n[[Category:Lists of cities in Europe|Britain, Roman]]\n[[Category:Lists of place names|Britain]]\n[[Category:Lists of places in the United Kingdom|Roman]]\n[[Category:Roman Britain-related lists|Place names]]\n[[Category:Lists of cities by toponymy|Britain]]\n\n[[pt:Top\u00f3nimos romanos no Reino Unido]]\n", "name_user": "Douglal", "label": "safe", "comment": "Lutudarum added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Roman_place_names_in_Britain"}
{"title_page": "323", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Year dab|323|the year in BC|323 BC|the car|Mazda 323}}\n{{unreferenced|date=November 2017}}\n{{Year nav|323}}\n{{M1 year in topic}}\nYear '''323''' ('''[[Roman numerals|CCCXXIII]]''') was a [[common year starting on Tuesday]] (link will display the full calendar) of the [[Julian calendar]]. At the time, it was known as the '''Year of the Consulship of Severus and Rufinus''' (or, less frequently, '''year 1076 ''[[Ab urbe condita]]'''''). The denomination 323 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the [[Anno Domini]] [[calendar era]] became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.\n\n== Events ==\n<onlyinclude>\n=== By place ===\n==== Roman Empire ====\n* Emperor [[Constantine the Great]] defeats the invading [[Goths]] and [[Sarmatians]] north of the [[Danube]] in [[Dacia]], and claims the title of ''[[List of Imperial Roman victory titles|Sarmaticus Maximus]]''.\n\n==== China ====\n* Crown Prince [[Emperor Ming of Jin|Jin Mingdi]] succeeds [[Emperor Yuan of Jin|Jin Yuandi]] as [[emperor]] of the [[Jin Dynasty (265-420)|Eastern Jin Dynasty]].\n</onlyinclude>\n=== By topic ===\n====Religion====\n* The poetic work ''Banquet'' (''Thalia'') by the Libyan-born Egyptian Christian priest [[Arius]], age 73, expresses the doctrine that [[Jesus|Jesus of Nazareth]] was not of the same substance as [[God]] but rather had a finite nature. As [[ascetic]] he leads a Christian community near [[Alexandria]] and comes under suspicion of [[heresy]]. Arius writes to his former schoolmate [[Eusebius of Nicomedia|Eusebius]], bishop of [[Nicomedia]], asking for support. Eusebius writes to other [[bishop]]s, and when Arius is condemned in September, Eusebius gives him safe haven, and sponsors a [[synod]] at [[Bithynia]] in October, which nullifies Arius's [[excommunication]] (see [[First Council of Nicaea|Council of Nicaea]], [[325]] AD).\n\n== Births ==\n* [[Constans|Constans I]], [[Roman Emperor]] (approximate date)\n\n== Deaths ==\n* [[January 3]] &ndash; [[Emperor Yuan of Jin|Jin Yuandi]], emperor of the [[Jin Dynasty (265-420)|Jin Dynasty]] (b. [[276]])\n* [[Zhang Bin (Later Zhao)|Zhang Bin]], Chinese strategist of the [[Jie people|Jie]] state [[Later Zhao]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:323}}\n[[Category:323| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Year dab|323|the year in BC|323 BC|the car|Mazda 323}}\n{{unreferenced|date=November 2017}}\n{{Year nav|323}}\n{{M1 year in topic}}\nYear '''323''' ('''[[Roman numerals|CCCXXIII]]''') was a [[common year starting on Tuesday]] (link will display the full calendar) of the [[Julian calendar]]. At the time, it was known as the '''Year of the Consulship of Severus and Rufinus''' (or, less frequently, '''year 1076 ''[[Ab urbe condita]]'''''). The denomination 323 for this year has been used since the early medieval period, when the [[Anno Domini]] [[calendar era]] became the prevalent method in Europe for naming years.\n\n== Events ==\n<onlyinclude>\n=== By place ===\n==== Roman Empire ====\n* Emperor [[Constantine the Great]] defeats the invading [[Goths]] and [[Sarmatians]] north of the [[Danube]] in [[Dacia]], and claims the title of ''[[List of Imperial Roman victory titles|Sarmaticus Maximus]]''.\n\n==== China ====\n* Crown Prince [[Emperor Ming of Jin|Jin Mingdi]] succeeds [[Emperor Yuan of Jin|Jin Yuandi]] as [[emperor]] of the [[Jin Dynasty (265-420)|Eastern Jin Dynasty]].\n</onlyinclude>\n=== By topic ===\n====Religion====\n* The poetic work ''Banquet'' (''Thalia'') by the Libyan-born Egyptian Christian priest [[Arius]], age 73, expresses the doctrine that [[Jesus|Jesus of Nazareth]] was not of the same substance as [[God]] but rather had a finite nature. As [[ascetic]] he leads a Christian community near [[Alexandria]] and comes under suspicion of [[heresy]]. Arius writes to his former schoolmate [[Eusebius of Nicomedia|Eusebius]], bishop of [[Nicomedia]], asking for support. Eusebius writes to other [[bishop]]s, and when Arius is condemned in September Eusebius gives him safe haven and sponsors a [[synod]] at [[Bithynia]] in October which nullifies Arius's [[excommunication]] (see [[First Council of Nicaea|Council of Nicaea]], [[325]] AD).\n\n== Births ==\n* [[Constans|Constans I]], [[Roman Emperor]] (approximate date)\n\n== Deaths ==\n* [[January 3]] &ndash; [[Emperor Yuan of Jin|Jin Yuandi]], emperor of the [[Jin Dynasty (265-420)|Jin Dynasty]] (b. [[276]])\n* [[Zhang Bin (Later Zhao)|Zhang Bin]], Chinese strategist of the [[Jie people|Jie]] state [[Later Zhao]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:323}}\n[[Category:323| ]]\n", "name_user": "Histrydude", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/323"}
{"title_page": "(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox single\n| name       = (Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\n| cover      = (Just_Like)_Romeo_and_Juliet_-_The_Reflections.jpg\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[the Reflections (Detroit band)|The Reflections]]\n| album      = (Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\n| B-side     = Can't You Tell By the Look in My Eyes\n| released   = February 1964<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/gw89|title=The Reflections [Detroit] - (Just Like) Romeo And Juliet|via=www.45cat.com}}</ref>\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|Vinyl record]] <small>(7\" 45 RPM)</small>\n| recorded   = 1964\n| studio     = [[Golden World Records]] Studio\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[doo-wop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Golden World Records]]\n| writer     = Bob Hamilton, <br> [[Freddie Gorman]]\n| producer   = Rob Reeco\n| prev_title = You Said Goodbye\n| prev_year  = 1963\n| next_title = Like Columbus Did\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\n'''\"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\"''' is the title of a 1964 hit single by [[the Reflections (Detroit band)|The Reflections]], their recording of a composition by Bob Hamilton and [[Freddie Gorman]].\n\nEd Wingate, owner of the newly formed Detroit-based [[Golden World Records]], had signed the Reflections on the basis of the group's regional success with the single \"You Said Goodbye\" on the local Kay-Ko label. Songwriter Freddie Gorman, who had been recruited by Golden World from [[Motown]], would recall that he considered his recent composition \"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\" as \"tailor made\" for the [[doo-wop]]-styled Reflections \"because it had a pop feel, as opposed to the R&B thing they were doing.\" However Reflections' lead singer Tony Micale recalls that none of the group responded positively to the song when Gorman first sang it for them: \"It just didn't sound like much with [Gorman] just playing a little piano backup\".<ref name=\"Grit, Noise, & Revolution\">{{cite book\n| first=David A.\n| last=Carson\n| year=2005\n| title=Grit, Noise, & Revolution: the birth of Detroit rock n' roll\n| edition=1st paperback\n| publisher=University of Michigan Press\n| location=Ann Arbor MI\n| pages=53\u201354\n| isbn=978-0-472-03190-0}}</ref>\n\nThe Reflections recorded the vocal for the track several weeks later at the RCA recording studio in Chicago. According to Micale, the group's members still regarded the song as somewhat of a joke. While running through the song prior to the recording session they ad-libbed a [[falsetto]] \"doo-doo-doot\" hook line as irreverent mimicry of Gorman's vocal style when he'd pitched them the song. The group was surprised when Gorman added that line to the song's vocal arrangement.<ref>[http://kool.cbslocal.com/2011/04/19/this-song-started-out-as-a-joke/ This Song Started Out As A Joke \u00ab 94.5 KOOL FM<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The instrumental track for \"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\" had been recorded at [[United Sound Systems]] in Detroit. Micale would recall that when the group's members first heard that instrumental track through the [RCA] studio monitors \"we were just blown away... Some of the Motown [session musicians] were playing on it, and the sound was just amazing. Besides our vocals, the only thing added at that point were [the] 'doo-doo-doot's that we had come up with, and hand claps\".<ref name=\"Grit, Noise, & Revolution\"/>\n\n==Chart history==\n\nFirst aired on [[CKLW]] in [[Windsor, Ontario|Windsor ON]] in February 1964, the single topped the hit parade of CKLW, as well as those of Detroit radio stations [[WJBK]] and [[WNIC|WKNR]] in March 1964. \"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\" made its national chart debut on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] dated April 11, 1964, ranked at #86 and rose to a Hot 100 peak of #6 on the chart dated May 30, 1964.  In New Zealand, the song reached number five.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=Lever+hit+parades&qyear=1964&qmonth=Jul&qweek=09-Jul-1964#n_view_location|title=flavour of new zealand - Lever hit parades|website=www.flavourofnz.co.nz}}</ref>\n\n==Cover versions==\nGarage-rock band [[Michael and the Messengers]] released a cover version of the song as a single in 1967. While their recording failed to crack the Hot 100, it eventually gained notoriety due to its inclusion on the 1972 compilation album ''[[Nuggets: Original Artyfacts from the First Psychedelic Era, 1965\u20131968]]''.\n\nIn 1969, the [[psychedelic rock]] band of [[Boston]] [[Ultimate Spinach]] released their unsuccessful cover version as a single and was included in their third and final album ''[[Ultimate Spinach III]]''.\n\n\"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\" returned to the Hot 100 in 1975 via a remake by [[Sha Na Na]] which, despite falling short of the [[Top 40]] with a #55 peak (and #47 [[Easy Listening]]), would remain the group's most successful single. A rival remake by [[Starz (band)|Fallen Angels]] reached #106 on the bubbling under the Hot 100 chart.\n\nIn 1980, a remake of \"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\" by [[Mental As Anything]] reached #27 in Australia.\n\nThe song has also been recorded by [[Little Caesar and the Consuls]] (album ''Little Caeser and the Consuls''/ 1965), [[The Outsiders (American band)|The Outsiders]] (album ''Album #2''/ 1966), [[Ultimate Spinach]] (album ''Ultimate Spinach III''/ 1969), and [[Stephen Bishop (singer)|Stephen Bishop]] (album ''Blue Guitars''/ 1996).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Mental As Anything|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Just Like) Romeo and Juliet}}\n[[Category:1964 songs]]\n[[Category:1964 singles]]\n[[Category:1980 singles]]\n[[Category:Mental As Anything songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Freddie Gorman]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox single\n| name       = (Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\n| cover      = (Just_Like)_Romeo_and_Juliet_-_The_Reflections.jpg\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[the Reflections (Detroit band)|The Reflections]]\n| album      = (Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\n| B-side     = Can't You Tell By the Look in My Eyes\n| released   = February 1964<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/gw89|title=The Reflections [Detroit] - (Just Like) Romeo And Juliet|via=www.45cat.com}}</ref>\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|Vinyl record]] <small>(7\" 45 RPM)</small>\n| recorded   = 1964\n| studio     = [[Golden World Records]] Studio\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[doo-wop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = [[Golden World Records]]\n| writer     = Bob Hamilton, <br> [[Freddie Gorman]]\n| producer   = Rob Reeco\n| prev_title = You Said Goodbye\n| prev_year  = 1963\n| next_title = Like Columbus Did\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\n'''\"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\"''' is the title of a 1964 hit single by [[the Reflections (Detroit band)|The Reflections]], their recording of a composition by Bob Hamilton and [[Freddie Gorman]].\n\nEd Wingate, owner of the newly formed Detroit-based [[Golden World Records]], had signed the Reflections on the basis of the group's regional success with the single \"You Said Goodbye\" on the local Kay-Ko label. Songwriter Freddie Gorman, who had been recruited by Golden World from [[Motown]], would recall that he considered his recent composition \"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\" as \"tailor made\" for the [[doo-wop]]-styled Reflections \"because it had a pop feel, as opposed to the R&B thing they were doing.\" However Reflections' lead singer Tony Micale recalls that none of the group responded positively to the song when Gorman first sang it for them: \"It just didn't sound like much with [Gorman] just playing a little piano backup\".<ref name=\"Grit, Noise, & Revolution\">{{cite book\n| first=David A.\n| last=Carson\n| year=2005\n| title=Grit, Noise, & Revolution: the birth of Detroit rock n' roll\n| edition=1st paperback\n| publisher=University of Michigan Press\n| location=Ann Arbor MI\n| pages=53\u201354\n| isbn=978-0-472-03190-0}}</ref>\n\nThe Reflections recorded the vocal for the track several weeks later at the RCA recording studio in Chicago. According to Micale, the group's members still regarded the song as somewhat of a joke. While running through the song prior to the recording session they ad-libbed a [[falsetto]] \"doo-doo-doot\" hook line as irreverent mimicry of Gorman's vocal style when he'd pitched them the song. The group was surprised when Gorman added that line to the song's vocal arrangement.<ref>[http://kool.cbslocal.com/2011/04/19/this-song-started-out-as-a-joke/ This Song Started Out As A Joke \u00ab 94.5 KOOL FM<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The instrumental track for \"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\" had been recorded at [[United Sound Systems]] in Detroit. Micale would recall that when the group's members first heard that instrumental track through the [RCA] studio monitors \"we were just blown away... Some of the Motown [session musicians] were playing on it, and the sound was just amazing. Besides our vocals, the only thing added at that point were [the] 'doo-doo-doot's that we had come up with, and hand claps\".<ref name=\"Grit, Noise, & Revolution\"/>\n\n==Chart history==\n\nFirst aired on [[CKLW]] in [[Windsor, Ontario|Windsor ON]] in February 1964, the single topped the hit parade of CKLW, as well as those of Detroit radio stations [[WJBK]] and [[WNIC|WKNR]] in March 1964. \"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\" made its national chart debut on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] dated April 11, 1964, ranked at #86 and rose to a Hot 100 peak of #6 on the chart dated May 30, 1964.  In New Zealand, the song reached number five.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=Lever+hit+parades&qyear=1964&qmonth=Jul&qweek=09-Jul-1964#n_view_location|title=flavour of new zealand - Lever hit parades|website=www.flavourofnz.co.nz}}</ref>\n\n==Cover versions==\nGarage-rock band [[Michael and the Messengers]] released a cover version of the song as a single in 1967. While their recording failed to crack the Hot 100, it eventually gained notoriety due to its inclusion on the 1972 compilation album ''[[Nuggets: Original Artyfacts from the First Psychedelic Era, 1965\u20131968]]''.\n\nIn 1969, the [[psychedelic rock]] band of [[Boston]] [[Ultimate Spinach]] released their unsuccessful cover version as a single and was included in their third and final album ''[[Ultimate Spinach III]]''.\n\n\"(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\" returned to the Hot 100 in 1975 via a remake by [[Sha Na Na]] which, despite falling short of the [[Top 40]] with a #55 peak (and #47 [[Easy Listening]]), would remain the group's most successful single. A rival remake by [[Starz (band)|Fallen Angels]] reached #106 on the bubbling under the Hot 100 chart.\n\nThe song has also been recorded by [[Little Caesar and the Consuls]] (album ''Little Caeser and the Consuls''/ 1965), [[The Outsiders (American band)|The Outsiders]] (album ''Album #2''/ 1966), [[Ultimate Spinach]] (album ''Ultimate Spinach III''/ 1969), and [[Stephen Bishop (singer)|Stephen Bishop]] (album ''Blue Guitars''/ 1996).\n\n== Mental's version ==\n\n(Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\" was recorded by Australian band [[Mental As Anything]], released in 1980 and it reached number 27 on the [[Kent Music Report]].<ref>[http://www.australianmusicdatabase.com/recordings/just-like-romeo-and-juliet-by-mental-as-anything Australian Music Database - Mental As Anything - (Just Like) Romeo And Juliet]</ref>\n\n{{Infobox single\n| name       = (Just Like) Romeo and Juliet\n| cover      = \n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mental As Anything]]\n| album      = \n| B-side     = Go Down\n| released   = November 1980 <ref>[http://www.45cat.com/record/k8115 45cat - Mental As Anything - (Just Like) Romeo And Juliet]</ref>\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|Vinyl record]], 7\"\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = \n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Rock (music)|Rock]]\n| length     = 2:12\n| label      = [[Regular Records]]\n| writer     = Bob Hamilton, <br> [[Freddie Gorman]]\n| producer   = Cameron Allan\n| prev_title = [[Come Around (Mental As Anything song)|Come Around]]\n| prev_year  = 1980\n| next_title = [[If You Leave Me, Can I Come Too?]]\n| next_year  = 1981\n}}\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = \n\n| title1          = (Just Like) Romeo And Juliet\n| writer1         = Bob Hamilton, [[Freddie Gorman]]\n| length1         = 2:12\n\n| title2          = Go Down \n| writer2         = [[Martin Plaza]]\n| length2         = 2:44\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* [[Martin Plaza]] &mdash; lead vocals, guitar    \n* [[Greedy Smith]] &mdash; lead vocals, keyboards, harmonica\n* [[Reg Mombassa]] &mdash; guitar, vocals  \n* [[Peter O'Doherty]] &mdash; bass, guitar, vocals \n* [[David Twohill|Wayne de Lisle]] \u2013 drums\n\n== Chart performance ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Chart (1980)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australian [[Kent Music Report]]<ref name=\"Kent\">{{cite book |title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970&ndash;1992]] |last=Kent |first=David |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |publisher=Australian Chart Book |location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives]], NSW |year=1993 |isbn=0-646-11917-6 }}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"| 18\n|-\n|}\n\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Mental As Anything|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Just Like) Romeo and Juliet}}\n[[Category:1964 songs]]\n[[Category:1964 singles]]\n[[Category:1980 singles]]\n[[Category:1980 songs]]\n[[Category:Mental As Anything songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Freddie Gorman]]\n[[Category:Regular Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "The Lord of Math", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Reverted edits byJukeboxMan1990(talk) to last version by MarnetteD)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/(Just_Like)_Romeo_and_Juliet"}
{"title_page": "\u00c9vry Schatzman", "text_new": "{{short description|French astronomer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{ infobox Scientist\n| name        = \u00c9vry Schatzman\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1920|09|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], [[France]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2010|04|25|1920|09|16|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Paris]], France\n| nationality = French\n| education   = [[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure (Paris)|\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure]]<br>[[University of Paris]]\n| fields      = [[Astrophysics]]\n| spouse      = Ruth Fischer\n| children    = [[Michelle Schatzman]]\n| awards      = [[CNRS]] Gold Medal\n}}\n\n'''\u00c9vry L\u00e9on Schatzman''' (16 September 1920 &ndash; 25 April 2010<ref>http://www.union-rationaliste.org/index.php/20100427351/Informations/Deces-d-Evry-Schatzman.html  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808104805/http://www.union-rationaliste.org/index.php/20100427351/Informations/Deces-d-Evry-Schatzman.html |date=8 August 2010 }}</ref>) was a French [[astrophysicist]].<ref>p. 104, ''L'Outil Th\u00e9orie'', Evry Schatzman and Isabelle Souriau, Paris: Eshel, 1992.  {{ISBN|2-906704-44-X}}.</ref><ref name=\"iac\">[http://www.iac.es/gabinete/iacnoticias/2-99/evry.htm EVRY SCHATZMAN y la historia de la evoluci\u00f3n estelar], Bego\u00f1a L\u00f3pez Betancor, ''I@C Noticias'', Instituto de Astrof\u00edsica de Canarias, 2-1999.  Accessed on line 20 September 2007.</ref>\n\nHis father, Benjamin Schatzman, was a [[dentist]] born in [[Tulcea]], Romania and emigrated at a young age with his family to Palestine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.agoravox.fr/actualites/technologies/article/evry-schatzman-le-savant-des-77462|author=Sylvain Rakotoarison |title=\u00c9vry Schatzman, le savant des astres|work=AgoraVox|date=25 June 2010|accessdate=13 August 2010|language=French}}</ref> Schatzman began his studies at the [[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure (Paris)|\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure]] in November 1939.  After the [[German military administration in occupied France during World War II|German invasion of France]], Schatzman, who was [[Jewish]], fled [[occupied France]], arriving in [[Lyon]] in January 1942.  He worked there for a year and then moved to [[Haute-Provence Observatory]] where he hid under the pseudonym Antoine Emile Louis Sellier.<ref>{{cite arXiv |last=Luminet |first=Jean-Pierre |author-link=Jean-Pierre Luminet |eprint=1503.08328 |title=Evry L\u00e9on Schatzman |class=physics.hist-ph |date=28 March 2015 }}</ref> He was hired by the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique]] (CNRS) in the fall of 1945 and received his [[doctorate]] in March 1946.  He spent time at [[Copenhagen Observatory]] and [[Princeton University]] before beginning to teach at the [[University of Paris]] in 1949, where he remained for 27 years.  His daughter, mathematician [[Michelle Schatzman]] was born in 1949. He was long at the [[Institut d'astrophysique de Paris|Institut d'Astrophysique]], a CNRS organization built in the garden side of l'Observatoire.  During this period Schatzman also taught at the [[Universit\u00e9 Libre de Bruxelles]] ({{lang-en|Free University of Brussels}}).  Schatzman became an associate professor at the University of Paris in 1954.  In 1976 he moved to [[Nice Observatory]], where he eventually became a full researcher.  Schatzman retired in the fall of 1989.<ref name=\"desire\">[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996ARA&A..34....1S The Desire To Understand the World], Evry Schatzman, ''Annual Review of Astronomy and Astrophysics'' '''34''' (1996), pp. 1\u201334.  DOI [https://dx.doi.org/10.1146/annurev.astro.34.1.1 10.1146/annurev.astro.34.1.1].</ref>\n\nSchatzman worked on [[white dwarf]]s during the 1940s.  He realized that the atmospheres of white dwarfs should be gravitationally stratified, with [[hydrogen]] on top and heavier elements below,<ref>[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1945AnAp....8..143S Th\u00e9orie du d\u00e9bit d'\u00e9nergie des naines blanches], Evry Schatzman, ''Annales d'Astrophysique'' '''8''' (January 1945), pp. 143\u2013209.</ref><ref name=\"physrev\">[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1990RPPh...53..837K Physics of white dwarf stars], D. Koester and G. Chanmugam, ''Reports on Progress in Physics'' '''53''' (1990), pp. 837\u2013915.</ref><sup>, \u00a75\u20136</sup> and explained [[pressure ionization]] in white dwarf atmospheres.<ref name=\"desire\" /> He was one of the proponents of the wave heating theory of the [[solar corona]].<ref>[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1981ARA&A..19....7K On the theory of coronal heating mechanisms], Max Kuperus, James A. Ionson, and Daniel S. Spicer, ''Annual Review of Astronomy and Astrophysics'' '''19''' (1981), pp. 7\u201340.</ref><ref>[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1949AnAp...12..203S The heating of the solar corona and chromosphere], Evry Schatzman, ''Annales d'Astrophysique'' '''12''' (1949), pp. 203\u2013218.</ref> Schatzman proposed the mechanism of [[magnetic braking]], by which [[Stellar wind|outflows]] slow down the stellar rotation.<ref>[[Leon Mestel|Mestel, L.]], 1968, ''MNRAS'', '''138''', 359\u2013391</ref>\n\nSchatzman wrote the astrophysics textbook ''Astrophysique G\u00e9n\u00e9rale'' and contributed greatly to the popularity of astrophysics in France.  He received the [[Prix Jules Janssen]] of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 astronomique de France]] (French Astronomical Society) in 1973, the [[Holweck Prize]] in 1985, and the Gold Medal of the CNRS in 1983.  He became a member of the [[French Academy of Sciences]] in 1985.<ref name=\"iac\" /><ref name=\"desire\" />\n\nIn 1992 the [[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]] (CSICOP) presented Schatzman with their ''Distinguished Skeptic'' Award.<ref name=\"Dallas 1992\">{{cite journal|title=CSICOP's 1992 Awards|journal=Skeptical Inquirer|date=1993|volume=17|issue=3|page=236}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''Origine et \u00e9volution des mondes'', Paris: A. Michel, 1957.  Translated into Spanish by Raquel Rabiela de Gortari and [[Arcadio Poveda]] as ''Origen y evoluci\u00f3n del universo'', M\u00e9xico: UNAM, 1960; translated into English by Bernard and Annabel Pagel as ''The origin and evolution of the universe'', New York: Basic Books, 1965.\n* ''White Dwarfs'', Amsterdam: North-Holland, 1958.\n* (with [[Jean-Claude Pecker]]) ''Astrophysique G\u00e9n\u00e9rale'', Paris: Masson, 1959.\n* ''Our Expanding Universe'', New York: McGraw\u2013Hill, 1992, {{ISBN|0-07-055174-X}}.\n* (with Fran\u00e7oise Praderie)  ''Les Etoiles'', Paris: Paris Inter\u00e9ditions et ed. du CNRS, 1990, {{ISBN|2-7296-0299-2}}.  Translated into English by A. R. King as [https://books.google.com/books?id=FtZ_cNTPv8gC ''The Stars''], Berlin: Springer, 1993, {{ISBN|3-540-54196-9}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schatzman, Evry}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Neuilly-sur-Seine]]\n[[Category:French Jews]]\n[[Category:French astronomers]]\n[[Category:French astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:French people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the French Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Skeptics]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]]\n[[Category:Officers of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:Holocaust survivors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French astronomer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{ infobox Scientist\n| name        = \u00c9vry Schatzman\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1920|09|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Neuilly-sur-Seine]], [[France]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2010|04|25|1920|09|16|df=yes}}\n| death_place = [[Paris]], France\n| nationality = French\n| education   = [[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure (Paris)|\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure]]<br>[[University of Paris]]\n| fields      = [[Astrophysics]]\n| spouse      = Ruth Fischer\n| children    = [[Michelle Schatzman]]\n| awards      = [[CNRS]] Gold Medal\n}}\n\n'''\u00c9vry L\u00e9on Schatzman''' (16 September 1920 &ndash; 25 April 2010<ref>http://www.union-rationaliste.org/index.php/20100427351/Informations/Deces-d-Evry-Schatzman.html  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808104805/http://www.union-rationaliste.org/index.php/20100427351/Informations/Deces-d-Evry-Schatzman.html |date=8 August 2010 }}</ref>) was a French [[astrophysicist]].<ref>p. 104, ''L'Outil Th\u00e9orie'', Evry Schatzman and Isabelle Souriau, Paris: Eshel, 1992.  {{ISBN|2-906704-44-X}}.</ref><ref name=\"iac\">[http://www.iac.es/gabinete/iacnoticias/2-99/evry.htm EVRY SCHATZMAN y la historia de la evoluci\u00f3n estelar], Bego\u00f1a L\u00f3pez Betancor, ''I@C Noticias'', Instituto de Astrof\u00edsica de Canarias, 2-1999.  Accessed on line 20 September 2007.</ref>\n\nHis father, Benjamin Schatzman, was a [[dentist]] born in [[Tulcea]], Romania and emigrated at a young age with his family to Palestine.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.agoravox.fr/actualites/technologies/article/evry-schatzman-le-savant-des-77462|author=Sylvain Rakotoarison |title=\u00c9vry Schatzman, le savant des astres|work=AgoraVox|date=25 June 2010|accessdate=13 August 2010|language=French}}</ref> Schatzman began his studies at the [[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure (Paris)|\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure]] in November 1939.  After the [[German military administration in occupied France during World War II|German invasion of France]], Schatzman, who was [[Jewish]], fled [[occupied France]], arriving in [[Lyon]] in January 1942.  He worked there for a year and then moved to [[Haute-Provence Observatory]] where he hid under the pseudonym Antoine Emile Louis Sellier.<ref>{{cite arXiv |last=Luminet |first=Jean-Pierre |author-link=Jean-Pierre Luminet |eprint=1503.08328 |title=Evry L\u00e9on Schatzman |class=physics.hist-ph |date=28 March 2015 }}</ref> He was hired by the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique]] (CNRS) in the fall of 1945 and received his [[doctorate]] in March 1946.  He spent time at [[Copenhagen Observatory]] and [[Princeton University]] before beginning to teach at the [[University of Paris]] in 1949, where he remained for 27 years.  His daughter, mathematician [[Michelle Schatzman]] was born in 1949. He was long at the [[Institut d'astrophysique de Paris|Institut d'Astrophysique]], a CNRS organization built in the garden side of l'Observatoire.  During this period Schatzman also taught at the [[Universit\u00e9 Libre de Bruxelles]] ({{lang-en|Free University of Brussels}}).  Schatzman became an associate professor at the University of Paris in 1954.  In 1976 he moved to [[Nice Observatory]], where he eventually became a full researcher.  Schatzman retired in the fall of 1989.<ref name=\"desire\">[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1996ARA&A..34....1S The Desire To Understand the World], Evry Schatzman, ''Annual Review of Astronomy and Astrophysics'' '''34''' (1996), pp. 1\u201334.  DOI [https://dx.doi.org/10.1146/annurev.astro.34.1.1 10.1146/annurev.astro.34.1.1].</ref>\n\nSchatzman worked on [[white dwarf]]s during the 1940s.  He realized that the atmospheres of white dwarfs should be gravitationally stratified, with [[hydrogen]] on top and heavier elements below,<ref>[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1945AnAp....8..143S Th\u00e9orie du d\u00e9bit d'\u00e9nergie des naines blanches], Evry Schatzman, ''Annales d'Astrophysique'' '''8''' (January 1945), pp. 143\u2013209.</ref><ref name=\"physrev\">[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1990RPPh...53..837K Physics of white dwarf stars], D. Koester and G. Chanmugam, ''Reports on Progress in Physics'' '''53''' (1990), pp. 837\u2013915.</ref><sup>, \u00a75\u20136</sup> and explained [[pressure ionization]] in white dwarf atmospheres.<ref name=\"desire\" /> He was one of the proponents of the wave heating theory of the solar [[corona]].<ref>[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1981ARA&A..19....7K On the theory of coronal heating mechanisms], Max Kuperus, James A. Ionson, and Daniel S. Spicer, ''Annual Review of Astronomy and Astrophysics'' '''19''' (1981), pp. 7\u201340.</ref><ref>[http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1949AnAp...12..203S The heating of the solar corona and chromosphere], Evry Schatzman, ''Annales d'Astrophysique'' '''12''' (1949), pp. 203\u2013218.</ref> Schatzman proposed the mechanism of [[magnetic braking]], by which [[Stellar wind|outflows]] slow down the stellar rotation.<ref>[[Leon Mestel|Mestel, L.]], 1968, ''MNRAS'', '''138''', 359\u2013391</ref>\n\nSchatzman wrote the astrophysics textbook ''Astrophysique G\u00e9n\u00e9rale'' and contributed greatly to the popularity of astrophysics in France.  He received the [[Prix Jules Janssen]] of the [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 astronomique de France]] (French Astronomical Society) in 1973, the [[Holweck Prize]] in 1985, and the Gold Medal of the CNRS in 1983.  He became a member of the [[French Academy of Sciences]] in 1985.<ref name=\"iac\" /><ref name=\"desire\" />\n\nIn 1992 the [[Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]] (CSICOP) presented Schatzman with their ''Distinguished Skeptic'' Award.<ref name=\"Dallas 1992\">{{cite journal|title=CSICOP's 1992 Awards|journal=Skeptical Inquirer|date=1993|volume=17|issue=3|page=236}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n* ''Origine et \u00e9volution des mondes'', Paris: A. Michel, 1957.  Translated into Spanish by Raquel Rabiela de Gortari and [[Arcadio Poveda]] as ''Origen y evoluci\u00f3n del universo'', M\u00e9xico: UNAM, 1960; translated into English by Bernard and Annabel Pagel as ''The origin and evolution of the universe'', New York: Basic Books, 1965.\n* ''White Dwarfs'', Amsterdam: North-Holland, 1958.\n* (with [[Jean-Claude Pecker]]) ''Astrophysique G\u00e9n\u00e9rale'', Paris: Masson, 1959.\n* ''Our Expanding Universe'', New York: McGraw\u2013Hill, 1992, {{ISBN|0-07-055174-X}}.\n* (with Fran\u00e7oise Praderie)  ''Les Etoiles'', Paris: Paris Inter\u00e9ditions et ed. du CNRS, 1990, {{ISBN|2-7296-0299-2}}.  Translated into English by A. R. King as [https://books.google.com/books?id=FtZ_cNTPv8gC ''The Stars''], Berlin: Springer, 1993, {{ISBN|3-540-54196-9}}.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schatzman, Evry}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Neuilly-sur-Seine]]\n[[Category:French Jews]]\n[[Category:French astronomers]]\n[[Category:French astrophysicists]]\n[[Category:French people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the French Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:\u00c9cole Normale Sup\u00e9rieure alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Skeptics]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Committee for Skeptical Inquiry]]\n[[Category:Officers of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:Holocaust survivors]]\n", "name_user": "Netoholic", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:post-move link fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89vry_Schatzman"}
